            What Richmond loses when the writing fades.
          </h2>

          <div class="mt-16 lg:mt-20 space-y-8">
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
              data-animate="fade"
            >
              Ghost signs are anchors. They connect a block to its own past in a way that no historical marker or Wikipedia article can replicate. A bronze plaque tells you something happened here. A ghost sign shows you the evidence, still embedded in the brick, still responding to the rain.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              Geographers have a word for what happens when a city loses these kinds of physical markers: placelessness. A street becomes uniform, neutral, interchangeable with any other street in any other city. Ghost signs are the opposite of placelessness. They are physical proof that this block has a lineage: that real people built real businesses here and put their names on the wall by hand.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              When a ghost sign fades past the point of recognition, the building loses a piece of itself. When someone paints over it, that piece is erased permanently. There are no backups. There is no archive of what these signs looked like at full vibrancy. Once they are gone, they are gone.
            </p>
            <p
              class="font-body text-soft-gray"
              style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-lg); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);"
            >
              The same development pressure that is transforming Church Hill, Manchester, and Scott&rsquo;s Addition into desirable neighborhoods is accelerating the loss. New construction removes walls. Renovations sandblast surfaces. Property owners paint over fading letters without knowing what they are destroying. The paradox is that the neglect that preserved these signs for a century is now ending, and the investment replacing it does not always account for what is already on the wall.
            </p>
